Django templates are  designed to be designer (non-programmer) friendly, becase of its CMS/newspaper origins.<p>Mako's goal is to create a powerful, programmer friendly and FAST templating language .<p>A lot many times having code in templates is a faster way to develop, especially if the presentation layer is mostly intended to be used by a programmer.<p>Also, you <i>can</i> write mako code which has good separation of concerns.<p>How is : 
<% for r in rows %>
  ${r.name}
<% endfor %><p>less readable than :<p>{% for r in rows %}
 {{r.name}}
{% endfor %}
